				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The instruction word size for a microprocessor is the size it uses (internally) for a decoded opcode. It is not the register size and it is not the address bus width. The word size has no impact whatsoever on a programmer and that might be why it means "jack squat" to some.
<br />
<br />In the case of a 6502 it is a pretty obvious fact that the word size is 8 bits. An architecture's word size must not be confused with the programming term "word", which does have an impact on programmers, and for legacy reasons has come to refer to a 16-bit word.
<br />
<br />The OP was simply explaining that he decided to stick to this same convention despite the fact that the 6502 has an 8-bit word size, which makes perfect sense.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

