			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I have to agree that 6502 words are 8-bit. It has nothing to do with the ALU, nor holding an address; a word is technically not tied to any specific number of bits, it's a generic type that for most processors will be the external data bus and/or instruction width. Memory devices are frequently expressed as n x n-bit words where the width isn't even necessarily a power of 2. Early DRAM came in 1-bit words, so it would take 8 words in parallel to form a sufficient data bus for the 6502. Ancient mini computers may have like 50-bit words, but perhaps only 32-bit can be used for data leaving 18-bits for dedicated instruction encoding. This scheme far predates the 8086 but also fits the 8086 which has a 16-bit bus; reading a DWORD or double word thus denotes two 16-bit memory fetches. (Despite the 8088 having an 8-bit bus, the programming model is identical so they kept the notation.)</div>

					
							<br /><br />
